  "prompt": "What are the all time best hollywood movies?",
  "response": "Determining the \"all-time best\" Hollywood movies can be subjective and often depends on personal preferences, critical acclaim, cultural impact, and historical significance. However, there are several films that consistently appear on lists of the greatest movies ever made. Here are some of the most acclaimed and influential Hollywood films:\n\n### Classic Hollywood:\n1. **Citizen Kane (1941)** \u2013 Directed by Orson Welles, often considered the greatest film ever made.\n2. **Gone with the Wind (1939)** \u2013 Directed by Victor Fleming, a sweeping epic about the American Civil War.\n3. **Casablanca (1942)** \u2013 Directed by Michael Curtiz, a timeless romance set during World War II.\n4. **The Wizard of Oz (1939)** \u2013 Directed by Victor Fleming, a beloved musical fantasy.\n5. **Singin' in the Rain (1952)**\u2013 Directed by Stanley Donen and Gene Kelly, a quintessential Hollywood musical.\n\n### Epic and Historical:\n6. **Lawrence of Arabia (1962)** \u2013 Directed by David Lean, an epic historical drama.\n7. **Ben-Hur (1959)** \u2013 Directed by William Wyler, a monumental historical epic.\n8. **Schindler's List (1993)** \u2013 Directed by Steven Spielberg, a powerful Holocaust drama.\n\n### Crime and Thrillers:\n9. **The Godfather (1972)** and **The Godfather Part II (1974)** \u2013 Directed by Francis Ford Coppola, masterpieces of the gangster genre.\n10. **Goodfellas (1990)** \u2013 Directed by Martin Scorsese, a gripping tale of organized crime.\n11. **Pulp Fiction (1994)** \u2013 Directed by Quentin Tarantino, a groundbreaking crime film with nonlinear storytelling.\n\n### Drama and Romance:\n12. **The Shawshank Redemption (1994)** \u2013 Directed by Frank Darabont, a deeply moving tale of hope and friendship.\n13. **Forrest Gump (1994)** \u2013 Directed by Robert Zemeckis, a heartwarming story spanning decades of American history.\n14. **Titanic (1997)** \u2013 Directed by James Cameron, a romantic disaster epic.\n\n### Science Fiction and Fantasy:\n15. **Star Wars: Episode IV \u2013 A New Hope (1977)** \u2013 Directed by George Lucas, a groundbreaking space opera.\n16. **2001: A Space (1968)**Odyssey** \u2013 Directed by Stanley Kubrick, a visionary sci-fi masterpiece.\n17. **The Matrix (1999)** \u2013 Directed by the Wachowskis, a revolutionary sci-fi action film.\n\n### Animation:\n18. **Toy Story (1995)** \u2013 Directed by John Lasseter, the first fully computer-animated feature film.\n19. **Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937)** \u2013 Directed by David Hand, the first full-length animated feature.\n\n### Action and Adventure:\n20. **Raiders of the Lost Ark (1981)** \u2013 Directed by Steven Spielberg, an iconic adventure film.\n21. **Die Hard (1988)** \u2013 Directed by John McTiernan, a definitive action movie.\n22. **The Dark Knight (2008)** \u2013 Directed by Christopher Nolan, a critically acclaimed superhero film.\n\n### Comedy:\n23. **Some Like It Hot (1959)** \u2013 Directed by Billy Wilder, a classic comedy.\n24. **Annie Hall (1977)** \u2013 Directed by Woody Allen, a romantic comedy with a unique narrative style.\n\n### Westerns:\n25. **The Searchers (1956)** \u2013 Directed by John Ford, a quintessential Western.\n26. **Once Upon a Time in the West (1968)** \u2013 Directed by Sergio Leone, an epic Western.\n\nThese films have left a lasting legacy in the world of cinema and continue to be celebrated for their storytelling, direction, performances, and technical achievements.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
